<!-- Article Content -->
  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>In the fall of 2022, researchers at the University of Illinois Chicago published a finding that should have generated at least a footnote in every wellness piece promoting intermittent fasting to women. After eight weeks of time-restricted eating — the protocol that compresses daily food intake into a four- to six-hour window — DHEA levels dropped by roughly 14% in participants, according to a study funded by the National Institutes of Health and published by researchers at the University of Illinois Chicago. DHEA is the hormone fertility clinics prescribe to improve ovarian function and egg quality. The drop was statistically significant. It also remained within the normal reference range, and its clinical meaning, the authors noted, was unclear. What was clear: this was one of the only well-designed controlled trials to specifically examine how time-restricted eating affects sex hormones in women. Most of the research that built the IF consensus never looked.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-evidence-base-was-not-built-for-you" class="reveal">
  <h2>The evidence base was not built for you</h2>
  <p>The case for intermittent fasting rests on legitimate science. Insulin sensitivity, weight loss, lipid profiles — the findings are real, the trials are rigorous, and Krista Varady at UIC, whose lab produced the 2023 DHEA result, has been among the most methodologically serious investigators in the field. None of that is in dispute.</p>
  <p>What is in dispute is who the research actually studied. The foundational IF literature — the studies that established the metabolic rationale and informed everything from clinical guidance to app-based protocols — was built overwhelmingly on male subjects and, where women appeared, predominantly postmenopausal ones. These are not the same physiology. Postmenopausal women have already undergone the hormonal transition that ends cyclical reproductive function; their hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis runs a fundamentally different program. Findings that apply to them do not transfer automatically to a 32-year-old in the follicular phase of her cycle.</p>
  <p>Premenopausal women were excluded for a practical reason: their cycling hormones introduce variability that complicates trial design. They are harder to study. The consequence is an evidence base with a structural sex bias that the wellness industry then marketed as universal. No malice required. Just the ordinary logic of research efficiency, followed by extraordinarily incurious promotion.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-axis-that-monitors-hunger" class="reveal">
  <h2>The axis that monitors hunger</h2>
  <p>The mechanism connecting energy scarcity to reproductive disruption is textbook endocrinology — specifically, the same pathway implicated in functional hypothalamic amenorrhea, the condition that causes female athletes and women with restrictive eating patterns to lose their periods.</p>
  <p>The hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis is the body's reproductive command chain. At the top, the hypothalamus secretes gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) in precise pulses. Those pulses tell the pituitary to release LH and FSH, which instruct the ovaries to produce estrogen and progesterone. The chain is elegant, cyclical, and calibrated to one thing in particular: perceived energy availability.</p>
  <p>When the hypothalamus detects low fuel, it responds through kisspeptin — a neuropeptide that gates GnRH release. Kisspeptin neurons are sensitive to leptin, the signal for fat stores, and ghrelin, the hunger signal. Sustained energy deficit suppresses kisspeptin activity, slows GnRH pulsatility, and quietly downshifts the reproductive axis. The Endocrine Society's clinical practice guideline — developed with input from experts who have consulted for pharmaceutical companies marketing hormone therapies — identifies suppressed GnRH drive as the "final common pathway" of energy-related reproductive disruption, though critics argue it underplays non-pharma interventions like nutritional recovery. This is settled physiology. The fasting literature has largely failed to engage with it.</p>
  <aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The timing of meals is not, by itself, the likely culprit. The body cannot detect an 'eating window' as a category; it responds to actual energy availability."</p></aside>
  <p>Male physiology has an HPG axis too. Male reproductive function is substantially more resilient to short-term energy stress — the evolutionary logic differs. Women's bodies are calibrated to downregulate reproduction before resources run out. Men's bodies, by and large, are not. This is not a small distinction. It is the entire reason why the sex-parity assumption baked into most IF research is wrong.</p>
</section>
<section id="signal-noise-and-a-12-month-complication" class="reveal">
  <h2>Signal, noise, and a 12-month complication</h2>
  <p>The 2023 Kalam study deserves careful reading, because the version circulating in wellness media has simplified its conclusions in both directions.</p>
  <p>DHEA dropped by approximately 14% in premenopausal women after eight weeks of TRE. Statistically significant. But DHEA dropped by approximately 13% in the postmenopausal group — nearly identically. Testosterone, androstenedione, and sex hormone-binding globulin were unchanged in both groups. DHEA values in both groups remained within the normal reference range throughout. The study's authors concluded that short-term TRE "has little effect on sex hormone levels" and called for larger, adequately powered trials. The sample sizes were twelve premenopausal and eleven postmenopausal participants — preliminary data from a secondary analysis, not a verdict.</p>
  <div class="data-callout reveal"><p><strong>A contradicting study worth knowing</strong></p><p>In 2024, Lin et al. published a 12-month randomized controlled trial in the <em>European Journal of Clinical Nutrition</em> — again from Varady's group, funded by the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases — comparing TRE, daily caloric restriction, and a control group in 90 adults with obesity. Result: no significant changes in DHEA, testosterone, or SHBG in premenopausal women, postmenopausal women, or men over 12 months. The DHEA signal observed at 8 weeks did not persist — or did not appear — at one year in a larger study.</p></div>
  <p>So one small study found a transient DHEA signal. A larger, longer study found nothing. This could mean the drop normalizes with time. It could mean the 2023 analysis was underpowered. It could mean that the two protocols — 4–6 hour versus 8-hour eating windows, with different real-world caloric outcomes — are different enough to produce different results. Anyone claiming certainty in either direction is ahead of the data. That includes the IF evangelists who dismissed the 2023 finding as noise and the alarm merchants who declared it proof of harm.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-gap-between-trial-and-practice" class="reveal">
  <h2>The gap between trial conditions and lived practice</h2>
  <p>Varady's trials share a feature that distinguishes them from how most people actually fast: they are supervised, participants' intake is tracked, and the TRE conditions do not always produce extreme caloric deficits. When someone is told to eat freely within a four-hour window, they often consume less than they would across a full day — but not catastrophically less. The trials measure a controlled version of the intervention. Real-world practice is not controlled.</p>
  <p>The woman following a 16:8 protocol from a wellness app, simultaneously undereating because the compressed window suppresses appetite, running four days a week, managing a full-time job — she is not the subject in any of these trials. She is running her own experiment. The mechanism that connects energy scarcity to GnRH suppression does not care whether her deficit came from intermittent fasting or crash dieting. It responds to the signal, not the label.</p>
  <p>This is where the institutional failure becomes most visible. Not in suppressed data or deliberate deception, but in the gap between what trials measured and what a decade of aggressive IF marketing encouraged. The research showed metabolic benefits in men and postmenopausal women, with limited short-term hormonal disruption in supervised trials where caloric intake was adequate. What got transmitted: IF works for everyone, skip breakfast, optimize your metabolism. The nuance did not survive the journey from journal to app notification.</p>
</section>
<section id="who-is-actually-at-risk" class="reveal">
  <h2>Who is actually at risk</h2>
  <p>The evidence — limited as it is — points toward specific populations, not universal alarm.</p>
  <p>Lean, physically active premenopausal women are the group where GnRH suppression is most plausible. The hypothalamic amenorrhea literature is consistent: the condition strikes disproportionately in women already at the lower edge of energy balance, where even modest additional restriction crosses a threshold. Women with obesity in the TRE trials have a metabolic buffer lean women do not. The Kalam finding, whatever it means clinically, came from participants with obesity; its relevance to lean women is untested.</p>
  <p>Women chronically undereating during their eating windows face compounded risk. Caloric content matters more than timing. A protocol consistently producing a large daily deficit — whether by intention or because appetite suppression prevents adequate intake — is a different intervention from one that maintains energy balance. These are rarely distinguished in popular IF advice, which tends to treat the eating window as the variable that matters and everything else as detail.</p>
  <p>High chronic stress is a cofactor, not a footnote. The HPA and HPG axes interact directly: elevated cortisol suppresses kisspeptin release and is associated with lower LH secretion. Adding the physiological stress of sustained fasting to an already-activated stress response is not the same intervention as fasting under metabolic calm.</p>
  <p>Postmenopausal women appear to face lower hormonal risk from TRE. The 12-month Lin trial found no significant sex hormone changes in this group. The evidence here is more reassuring — though it remains far from complete.</p>
</section>
<section id="what-to-do-with-incomplete-data" class="reveal">
  <h2>What to do with an unfinished experiment</h2>
  <p>Adequately powered, long-term trials examining TRE's effect on the reproductive hormones of lean, premenopausal women eating at varying caloric levels do not exist. The women who adopted IF a decade ago based on male-derived data were, in a meaningful sense, running an uncontrolled experiment. That is not a reason for panic. It is a reason to demand better science and to treat the existing evidence with the calibrated confidence it actually warrants — not the certainty with which it has been sold.</p>
  <p>Several practical things follow. Menstrual cycle changes — lengthening, shortening, spotting, absence — are a real biomarker, not anecdote. The hypothalamic amenorrhea literature is explicit: the menstrual cycle is the earliest warning sign of HPG axis disruption. A woman who begins TRE and notices cycle changes should take them seriously, not normalize them as adaptation. The body is reporting a signal.</p>
  <p>Eating adequately during the eating window is not optional safety theater. Large, consistent deficits are the risk factor — not the window itself. A protocol that routinely suppresses intake below the energy threshold the hypothalamus requires is something to track, not assume away.</p>
  <p>And any IF protocol designed without reference to female physiology, the menstrual cycle, or reproductive endocrinology should be understood for what it is: designed for someone else. Because it was.</p>
</section>
